    <p>In <xref ref="fig_inverse4">Figure</xref> we see <m>f(x) = \sin x</m> and <m>f^{-1} = \sin^{-1} x</m> graphed on their respective domains. The line tangent to <m>\sin x</m> at the point <m>(\pi/3, \sqrt{3}/2)</m> has slope <m>\cos \pi/3 = 1/2</m>. The slope of the corresponding point on <m>\sin^{-1}x</m>, the point <m>(\sqrt{3}/2,\pi/3)</m>, is
      <me>
        \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-(\sqrt{3}/2)^2}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-3/4}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{1/4}} = \frac{1}{1/2}=2,
      </me>
      verifying yet again that at corresponding points, a function and its inverse have reciprocal slopes.</p>

    <p>Using similar techniques, we can find the derivatives of all the inverse trigonometric functions. In <xref ref="fig_domain_trig">Figure</xref> we show the restrictions of the domains of the standard trigonometric functions that allow them to be invertible.</p>

